        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The rms requirement is set by the aim to detect the C17O 3-2 line in 0.5 km/s channels (sufficient to marginally resolve the line of this face-on disk). Simple LTE calculations suggest a conservative line strength of 10 K (or 20 mJy in the 0.15" beam) for this line. We request a sensitivity of 5 mJy and expect to detect the line at 4sigma or more. This is sufficient to answer the question if the gas and dust have the same spatial distribution.
In the same integration time, the 5.6 GHz aggregated bandwidth provides a continuum rms of 0.07 mJy, allowing a S/N&gt;800 detection on the predicted continuum, more than enough to image the 20 au region we are interested in.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We record the C17O in 0.13 km/s wide channels that we can smooth down to 0.5 km/s if needed (but won't if enough S/N is reached). We apply a spectral averaging of 2 to reduce the data rate. The other three basebands are used to record the LSB and USB continuum to a total bandwidth of 5.6 GHz in TDM mode.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The 0.15" resolution nicely resolves the gap around 20 au (if it exists). At the same time, the corresponding array configuration recovers all scales out to the 2.3" diameter of the disk as seen in mm-emission. It is the perfect combination of resolution and MRS.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
