    <prp:abstract>TW Hya is one of the best studied planet-forming disks, thanks to its richness in gas and dust, close proximity, and near face-on orientation. Using ALMA Cycle 0 archival data, we have discovered a 870 micron continuum flux decrement at radii between 15 and 25 au in the disk, comparable to the location of Uranus in our Solar System. We explain this as the results of an empty gap (17-23 au) or a shadow (13-26 au) cast by the inner (few au) disk wall. The 0.5" resolution Cycle 0 data can not distinguish these scenarios, and recent H-band polarized intensity imaging equally allows both explanations. Here, we propose to image the TW Hya disk at 0.15" resolution in 870 micron continuum to determine if the disk has a gap or is shadowed, and in optically thin C17O 3-2 line emission to determine if the molecular gas shows a similar structure. We optimize our observational setup, and minimize observing time, to definitively answer if TW Hya's disk has a (planet-induced?) gap around 20 au or if its puffed-up inner disk wall casts a shadow across the disk at these radii.
</prp:abstract>
